column1: During the task, you first learned image pairs. For example, you first learned the book was paired with the woman. Later, you decided whether two images weighed more than a small dog. In this small dog task, you saw an image you had already learned (e.g., the book) with a new image (e.g., the alpaca).
column2: IN GENERAL, during the small dog task: When you saw an old image with a new pair, did you recall the earlier image pair (e.g., the woman)? Press 0 on your keyboard if you did not recall the earlier image pair, press 1 if you were actively trying to recall the earlier image pair, press 2 if the earlier image pair popped into mind without you trying.

column1: Did you recall the earlier image pair when you FIRST saw the new pair, during the arrow task, or both?
column2: Press 1 if you recalled the earlier image pair when you first encountered  the new pair. Press 2 if you mostly recalled the earlier image pair during the arrow task. Press 3 if the answer is both. Press 0 if you did not think of the earlier image pair. Note: this question is not asking about these specific images, but the other images  during the task.

column1: If you were thinking about the earlier image pair during the arrow task, how much of the arrow task were you thinking about it? Press 0, 1,  2, 3, 4 or 5.
column2: 0 = 0% to 9% of the time; 2 = 10 to 29%  of the time; 3 = 30 to 49%  of the time; 4 = 50 to 69%  of the time; 5 =  70 to 89%  of the time; 6 = 90 - 100% of the time.
